  <section id="introduction">
    <h2>1. Introduction</h2>
    <p>Peripheral devices are external devices connected to a computer to enhance its functionality. These devices allow the computer to interact with the outside world, processing input and output data effectively.</p>
    <img src="flowchart.png" alt="Peripheral Interaction Flowchart">
  </section>

  <section id="classification">
    <h2>2. Classification of Peripheral Devices</h2>
    <button class="collapsible">Click to Expand/Collapse</button>
    <div class="content">
      <p>Peripheral devices can be categorized as:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Input Devices</li>
        <li>Output Devices</li>
        <li>Storage Devices</li>
        <li>Input/Output Hybrid Devices</li>
      </ul>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Category</th>
            <th>Examples</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Input Devices</td>
            <td>Keyboard, Mouse, Microphone</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Output Devices</td>
            <td>Monitor, Printer, Speaker</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Storage Devices</td>
            <td>HDD, SSD, Flash Drives</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="input-devices">
    <h2>3. Input Devices</h2>
    <p>Input devices are tools used to provide data and control signals to a computer. Examples include:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><b>Keyboard:</b> Used for text input. Variants include mechanical and virtual keyboards.</li>
      <li><b>Mouse:</b> Optical, laser, and trackball mice enable cursor movement.</li>
      <li><b>Scanners:</b> Convert physical documents into digital formats.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section id="output-devices">
    <h2>4. Output Devices</h2>
    <p>Output devices display or produce data in human-readable formats. Examples:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><b>Monitor:</b> CRT, LED, and OLED technologies.</li>
      <li><b>Printers:</b> Inkjet, laser, and 3D printers.</li>
      <li><b>Speakers:</b> Produce sound for multimedia purposes.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section id="storage-devices">
    <h2>5. Storage Devices</h2>
    <p>Storage devices save data for future use. Examples include:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><b>Hard Drives:</b> Traditional storage with large capacities.</li>
      <li><b>Solid-State Drives:</b> Faster, reliable alternatives to HDDs.</li>
      <li><b>Flash Drives:</b> Portable and convenient for data transfer.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section id="trends">
    <h2>6. Emerging Trends in Peripheral Devices</h2>
    <p>The future of peripherals lies in innovation:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><b>VR/AR Devices:</b> Immersive technologies revolutionizing gaming and education.</li>
      <li><b>Wearables:</b> Smartwatches and fitness trackers for everyday use.</li>
      <li><b>Biometric Devices:</b> Fingerprint and retina scanners for security.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section id="conclusion">
    <h2>7. Conclusion</h2>
    <p>Peripheral devices play a vital role in modern computing. As technology advances, these devices will continue to shape how humans interact with computers, offering new possibilities and applications.</p>
  </section>

